ce:section.ce:para:
The crystallinity of the three typical CQDs is evaluated by XRD, as shown in Fig. 5
                        A. The XRD patterns exhibit a distinct broad peak at around 22.6°, which is indexed to the (100) planes of carbon and indicating that the three types CQDs have a graphite-like structure [26,27]. The appearance of this peak illustrates that the highly conjugated sp2 domain is closely packed within CQDs. Furthermore, to gain the features of the chemical bonds and functional groups in the CQDs, the FTIR spectra (Fig. 5B) and the XPS spectra (Fig. 6
                        ) are analyzed. As show in Fig. 5B, the three CQDs exhibit similar stretching vibration bands in the FTIR spectra, implying the presence of similar chemical compositions. Ulteriorly, the broad peak emerged at about 3200–3600 cm−1, ∼1205 cm−1 and ∼1626 cm−1 of the three CQDs can be ascribed to O–H/N–H, C–O and CO stretching vibration. Whereas the three signal peaks at 2840–2963, ∼1680, and ∼804 cm−1 are correspond to C–H (stretching vibration), CN (stretching vibration), and C–H (out-of-plane bending vibration), respectively. And that suggest the existence of the pyridine N. It's worth noting that the CO stretch gradually is increased from B-CQDs, G-CQDs to R-CQDs and the number of CN bond in G-CQDs seems to be substantially reduced [19,28–30]. Moreover, The CC (∼1462 cm−1), C–N (∼1334 cm−1) stretches bond confirms the existence of polyaromatic structures in the CQDs [31,32]. The FTIR spectra of the CQDs indicate that the multiple groups on the surface. Specifically, the carboxyl and amino groups tend to form a conjugated domain structure, which lead to numerous surface state emissive traps [33–35].
